{"cursor":"17873","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name=National Environmental Policy Act of 1969| fullname= National\n| Environmental Policy Act of 1969 acronym=NEPA enacted by=91st effective\n| date=January 1, 1970 public law url=\n| http://www.usinfo.org/enus/government/branches/nepaeqia.htm cite public law=\n| P.L. 91-190 cite statutes at large= 83 Stat. 852 (1969) acts amended= title\n| amended= 42 (Public Health and Welfare) sections created= et seq. sections\n| amended= leghisturl= introducedin= Senate| introducedbill= S. 1075\n| introducedby= Henry M. Jackson introduceddate= February 18, 1969 committees=\n| Senate Committee on Interior and Insular Affairs passedbody1= Senate\n| passeddate1= July 10, 1969 passedvote1= Unanimous passedbody2= House of\n| Representatives passeddate2= September 23, 1969 passedvote2= 372-15\n| conferencedate= December 17, 1969 passedbody3= Senate passeddate3= December\n| 20, 1969 passedvote3= passedbody4= House of Representatives passeddate4=\n| December 23, 1969 passedvote4= signedpresident= Richard Nixon signeddate=\n| January 1, 1970 amendments=Public Law 94-52, Jly 3, 1975, Public Law 94-83,\n| Aug 9, 1975 and Public Law 97-258, section 4(b), Sep 13, 1982\n}} The 'National Environmental Policy Act' ('NEPA') is a United States\nenvironmental law that established a U.S. national policy promoting the\nenhancement of the environment and also established the President's Council on\nEnvironmental Quality (CEQ). As one of the most emulated statutes in the world,\nNEPA has been called the modern-day equivalent of an âenvironmental Magna\nCartaâ. NEPA and Environmental Planning: Tools, Techniques, and Approaches\nfor Practitioners, CRC Press (2008).\n\nNEPA's most significant effect was to set up procedural requirements for all\nfederal government agencies to prepare environmental assessments (EAs) and\nenvironmental impact statements (EISs). EAs and EISs contain statements of the\nenvironmental effects of proposed federal agency actions. {{cite book\n  | last = U.S. Council on Environmental Quality (CEQ) first = authorlink =\n  | coauthors = title = A Citizen's Guide to the NEPA: Having Your Voice Heard\n  | publisher = date = December 2007 location = Washington, D.C. pages = 2â7 url\n  | = http://www.nepa.gov/nepa/Citizens_Guide_Dec07.pdf doi = id = isbn =\n  | accessdate = 2008-10-11}} NEPA's procedural requirements apply to all\n  | federal agencies in the executive branch. NEPA does not apply to the\n  | President, to Congress, or to the federal courts. CEQ.\n  | [http://ceq.hss.doe.gov/nepa/regs/ceq/1508.htm#1508.12 40 CFR Section\n  | 1508.12: Terminology: Federal agency.] Code of Federal Regulations.\n","linknr":261,"url":"National_Environmental_Policy_Act","recorded":1376418007,"links":["/w/index.php?title=National_Environmental_Policy_Act&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=National_Environmental_Policy_Act&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Environmental_Policy_Act","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/NEPA_(disamb